segments.text: Did you all ever do any research relating to the dairy industry, perhaps an ice cream?
We never did anything with dairy because dairy is not exactly a hot topic in this particular area.
See, I thought there might be an ice cream business in Washington County that might have had some link.
We are very protective of the ice cream business, and we don't want to cast anything.
dispersion of dairy cattle to have any problem.
They don't all live in Washington County.

As you look back now I'm serious again, as you look back on your years as department head, were there any research possibilities that were overlooked, but you now realize Oh, wish we'd done this or that?
We did about all we could do because research depended mainly upon somebody supporting it.
That, of course, comes from the fact that the university thinks that it should be funded research if it's going to be important.
And I was told very strongly one time that we're doing research.
We're studying natural diseases.
We're publishing.
And they said, well, that doesn't count, because if it doesn't bring money in, then it's not important.
I personally was impatient.
Some of my faculty did not perceive that the university members should have a curiosity and wish to pursue new knowledge, because they didn't feel that way, I guess.
So I think there were opportunities that were lost there.
During your years as department head, about what percentage of the budget for the department came from outside funding, outside the university?
I don't have any figures on that.
In the middle 70s, we had a
considerable budget, and I don't remember how many positions we had that were paid out of research, but there were five or six, I think.
All right, and those outside sources, what were some of them?
Well, we had support, like I told you, from the Kleberg Foundation, the National Institute for Health.
There were several programs with that around storage, had stuff on
neurologic disease and pathogenesis of that.
I don't know if you know what pathology and pathogenesis are the key word.
How does it come about?
And if you know how it comes about, then you know how to interact with it.
And we have worked, did some other work in collaboration with others.
Adams, for example, worked with a disease in horses.
that eating a type of Johnson grass that causes the inflammation of the bladder.
And then what it really tied down to was that it was a form of prussic acid poisoning.
Horses being unique, like cattle, it affects their blood.
And they have the oxygen carrying capacity, so they die from an oxygen.
But in horses, it's a slow process that affects the nerves.
And we worked that out fairly well.
And I thought it was an excellent experiment in the study of disease, although that disease is not highly important, except it's important to horse people to try to raise their horses on.
What was it that you did your masters on?
That was just a study of the relationship of bacteria to renal disease.
Was there anybody in the department that was the most successful grant getter, outside funding getter?
That would be hard to say.
We had a program which finally worked as a

In collaboration with the Parks and Wildlife, we developed a wild animal season program that came in and did very well and that was finally integrated with the Institute of Tropical Veterinarian Medicine.
There's a frequency of people trying to reorganize things.
The doctoral program was in existence when you became department head, and it grew to about how many students per year during your?
I think we had 12 to 13 at one time.
So you'd have three, four, five degrees doctoral per year completed?
Yeah, that time off took five, six years.
It depends on the aggressiveness of the individuals and their resourcefulness.
That's probably how it arrived, I guess.
And the department's funding came partly from the Ag Experiment Station?
After I became department head and soon after, well, when Ballantyne came, he set up a department of veterinary science, which worked through the Experiment Station.
And finally then that was broken up into departments.

It was only after I became department head, Hilton Smith had a little problem with the Experiment Station because of his prior experience with them, and he refused to work with them except on his terms.
And so then Al set that up and put me part-time at the Experiment Station, and we started
And it was a significant part then in later years.
Any from the Extension Service?
We really haven't had any relationship with Extension Service, per se.
Were there any other state agency funding sources?
Yes, we had $40,000 to $50,000, which today multiplied that today in the
We had studied the diseases of deer and things like that, and Mick Robinson started it.
One individual left, and then Mick Robinson took it over.
Any research that you remember as really fun, pleasant, really enjoyable?
The research that I did, I enjoyed.
was that study of natural disease.
And that, where you take what's there and try to figure it out.
And I think the fossilization problem was one.
Another thing we did with the physiology was on what they call crazy cow disease.
And that was a selenium toxicity.
And on selenium, the species included tomato and potato.
And they have solanins that are in there that force in the nervous system.
And working that out.
Ken had a project that he worked on, on his dissertation on a project on hip dysplasia of dogs, about chemistry of that in relation to hormones.
And the problem with that was that
to not become fun because it was such a logistic problem raising dogs.
We had about 300 dogs, Walker and American Foxhounds out there at one time.
And like I say, that's not fun.
When you retired in 76 as department head?
Oh, yeah, in 77.
When you retired in 77, do you think that veterinary pathology nationally, our veterinary pathology program, would have been the highest ranked of the veterinary programs here?
In ranking nationally, I would say within the top four.
And who were the others?
I think Cornell and Michigan.
Okay.
And Colorado wasn't bad.
Would there have been anybody else, any other department, any program here in the top three, four, five?
The graduate programs would be hard to relate.
The programs in focal diseases were strong as far as the research and the individual students, but they didn't have the PSD programs.
Dr. Price retired in the early 70s, and we looked for a new dean and ended up bringing back from Missouri a man that had gone to school at Texas A&M.
Do you remember that search?
For dean?
Mm-hmm.
I don't remember any in particular detail.
All right.
How did you all feel when Dr. Shelton was selected?
I thought I was pleased, basically.
George is not a hard person to get along with, and sometimes that was his fault.
I think we did well with George.
Everybody has their own peculiarities and you perceive them differently.
I was chairman of that committee, so I'm... Well, I figured that the reason he was selected because the board of directors from his hometown picked him.
Oh, I hadn't thought about that, no.
Those things always come up, Haskell, you know that.
Typist, this can be an editorial note.

When I went in as chairman of the search committee, I went in to Dr. Williams as president to report to him and Vice President Calhoun, and I had gone back personally to each of the subgroups that had been involved in the interview process.
the faculty representative, the student representatives, the former student representatives, U department heads, and so forth.
And I'd ask each group to rate all of the interviewees.
And it was my fault, I now realize it was foolish, my fault that we had interviewed eight prospective deans.
That's far too many.
Shouldn't have had that many.
But I had them each rate and gave eight points to the one they ranked first and right on down.
There were two that came out far above all the others.

A man who had been for a couple of years the dean at Ohio State, and then he literally told them to take the job and shove it, and he had left Ohio State in real anger, and they were angry at him and he was angry at them, and he had gone to Georgia just as a faculty member.
And the other one was Dr. Shelton.
And in my summary to President Williams, I said, oh, this man that's now in Georgia, he'll be exciting.
Now, there'll be all kinds of things.
You know, there'll be explosions.
There'll be anger.
But I mean, that place will really be hopping.
He said, tell me about this other man.
I said, well, I think he's calm.
He's methodical.
People can work with him.
He will work well, but quietly sort of, out there with the former students.
He'll work with the various constituencies.
And Dr. Williams quickly said, let's go with this second guy.
He said, I've got enough damn excitement in my life.
Were there any changes in style from Dean Price to Dean Shelton?
any way that the dean's office did things?
I don't remember much change.
I perceive that Dr. Sheldon was a little more student-oriented than Al.
Al was rather pragmatic, and as I told you before, he was a manager and a leader.
That was the only difference I saw, and Doc Sheldon was depending a lot more on opinions than Al did.
And he met regularly with you, department heads?
Now who under Dean Price, was there an associate dean?
Wallace Bay.
Wallace Bay was the last.
No, Shelton.
Shelton selected him.
Oh, Shelton?
Oh, no, I know.
Lyndon Kurtz was with Al, but he was not a veterinarian.
Jack Murray was assistant dean.
Oh, okay.
Was there anybody who was clearly the second in command?
That's what I was asking, where I'm headed.
Under Dean Price?
Dean Price?
Well, until he appointed a dean of research there wasn't, I think.
Who was that?
Fred Mauer.
Fred Mauer.
Oh, yeah, M-A-U-R-E-R.
Otherwise, I joked when I say the secretary.
All right.
Then when Dean Shelton, Joy Shelton, he soon appointed Wally Bay as the associate dean.
He took him out of pathology.
Don't pull that coffee cup off if it's got coffee in it.
No, he didn't.
He took him out of pathology.
Yeah.
Had you hired Dr. Bay?
Describe him and his manner and style.
a quiet gentleman of all, and a very congenial person, and as loyal an associate as you'd want to be the best next to me.
Right.
And in the way the leadership operated, if Dean, if you needed an answer and you could not contact Dean Shelton,
Could Wally Bay answer for him?
Could he say yes or no?
I don't know that I ever tested that.
Wallace would go along a lot and Doc Sheldon, he would ask opinions and kind of lead discussions and things like that and decisions would be made.
I never perceived that Wallace took to
a firm directorship of anything.

During all of your years on the faculty in veterinary medicine, do you remember any big complaints or examples of displeasure by the public out there wanting veterinary medicine to do something that they thought they weren't doing?
There was always a problem with a selection committee.
Oh, and admissions?
Oh, yeah.
Those things, and I think that occasionally something would happen with the clinic that people were upset with.
Other than that, I don't remember anything.
I don't remember anything.
Yeah.
We were told in a way, politically, we were told to keep our hands off.
And we really then, the program in veterinary medicine is you work with the practitioners.
And that's basically it.
Some people will bring animals in.
All right.
During your entire experience, how did the profession of veterinary medicine in Texas change?
What were the major shifts?
Well, I think it became a lot more sophisticated and international than they expected.
Actually, we produced quite a few graduates during this time.
I remember that 64 and then 128 veterinarians and they began to, I think, in a way saturate the
and of course those people were more innovative.
They went into different fields.
I think it was put into public health and things of this nature.
And all things change, and I think modernization, you might say, is the essence of it.
They also went into more exotic animals and birds, didn't they?
Oh, yeah.
I guess the biggest thing to me was the development of equine practitioners, for example.
Give some examples of some of the most unusual
animals or research or whatever it might be that you remember dealing with yourself.
There must have been some very unusual problems y'all had to solve.
Mick Robinson had a very interesting one that we never really resolved.
The deer in the Everest Plateau area, or at least that area, there were certain red granite gravel areas that when the deer would
would have sexual transformation.
I mean, they would lose their maleness and their antlers would never harden.
And I think we sort of looked at that for years.
And we had the usual things that happened.
You'd get a tiger here and occasionally even an elephant.
Where would they come from?
Well, usually from zoos or traveling zoos.
Oh, okay.
Either that or we would get them here, but they are the referrals with tigers and occasionally we would get exotic parrots and things like that.
Do you remember any famous person's animal or animals?
that y'all had to help with?
I don't.
We've got to stay clear of the people.
So you didn't, no governors, no Mr. Rutter's dog, you didn't help with Ranger or anything like that?
Most of those went after the clinic.
That's what I thought.
Anything we did,
We gave the report to the clinic and the clinic then represented what was stored.
And as far as the clinician is responsible, we found this or that and this kind of thing.
Do you remember any effort by anybody outside veterinary medicine to tell you all that you must or must not do any task?
Did any board member, politician, rich person, outside university administrator ever tried to micromanage?
No, I think we were isolated pretty much from that because they'd go to the clinic or something like that and they, there were certain things that happened there that I would not want to name.
It couldn't really be a legitimate answer.
We were forced to, we had to, of course faculty members that would make mistakes, they'd like to us as pathologists to handle that for them, but that was another story.
During your years on the faculty, were you on the admissions committee ever?
In the early years, yes.
In the early years.
Describe what that was like.
It was not, until those years, it was not a real problem except that where can we get enough people to fill this that are really unqualified.
There was a period in there that when we expanded over that that was the case.
Was that when first went from 64 to 128?
I think that was the general basic time, and they, there were a lot of students, you know, they just barely could stay in A&M.
They were applying, and the question I...
Compare the quality of the students in your later year, your last years, with the quality of the students in your first years on the faculty.
The students in the later years were academically much more sophisticated.
And I remember some of those students, the low score of their GPR might have been a 3.4 or something like that.
Where in the early years, particularly in the classes which I went through, that if you passed, you were in.
And back in those years, again, because of the way the dynamics of the situation were, some students took six, seven years to get through.
They just retook courses until they passed, because there was no such thing as there's so many slots.
And in the later years, of course, if you missed out, then you were out and you had to reapply to get back in if you missed or failed a course.
As coeducation began to be discussed here in the 60s, what did you and your colleagues in veterinary medicine think about the idea of coeducation?
Well, I don't think there was any opposition to it.
They thought it was rather incredulous that some young lay would want to do some of the things that veterinarians do.
But that's the maleness of the mind, I think, and we've been educated.
At that time, in the early 60s, were there many women nationally in veterinary medicine?
I don't remember a lot.
I think we went through the similar situation in most of them, although a lot of them did not have the restrictions that we had.
In pathology, a lot of them, the women, for example, went into pathology because it was
did not have the, it was a laboratory science, you might say.
And it was easier for them to, just women, to become involved in.
And they were some very, very competent individuals that did that.
And today, what's happening in veterinary pathology is just like it is in many, many new women in veterinary pathology.
Do you remember any important experiences in the department, either serious or humorous, as women became members of the student body?
Not that I want to repeat.
The selection committee has some interesting stories.
the whales or the applicants.
Were there some anecdotes and stories that faculty members used to tell that needed some censoring after coeducation began?
There were some people that were rather, I guess they were sensitive.
But I don't know that there was a bunch of them.
I think most of the people at that age that had been in medicine were pretty civilized, I'll say, or timid, either one way.
Do you remember, as department head, having to deal with any problem that was gender related with a student?
Not particularly, no.
Not in your department?
No.
That's what I was meaning.
We had a rather smooth sailing I think.
Our department was rather stern and felt that it had a serious charge to do.
If you could perceive Ken Pierce as you would expect him to relate to students.
I don't think the department is set that way.
For me as dean of faculties, the major problems that bounced to me relating to the entire program of veterinary medicine were the admissions.
That here was a good student who didn't get in because here were that many more that were better.
And the one I particularly remember, I was in Dr. Williams' office when he got a long-distance call from Oscar Wyatt, who literally was cussing him out.
I could hear he was yelling at him, and Dr. Williams at first was mad, and then he started laughing and held the phone out where I could hear it.
And Wyatt said, U.S.O.B., I'm going to get you fired.
And apparently he had promised his secretary that he could get her nephew or something or other, and his record was pitiful.
Well, when Dr. Williams hung up the phone, he turned to me and seriously said, let me ask, you know, let me throw an idea at you.
He said, what if I were to tell Veterinary Medicine to give 10 slots to be identified as presidential admissions?
What do you think?
I said, Dr. Williams, as soon as that word spreads, you will need 10 times 10 times 10.
There won't be enough slots if they're going to be done on that basis.

then and then he said yeah he said i didn't think it was work and i told him that i had never heard of that anywhere else uh like that and i said and i said why don't you to i know mr white won't be satisfied but to rational people tell them you know here's the search committee i don't pick them there's a group that does that they're serious
They may make a mistake, but if so, it's an honest mistake.
But I, as the president, am not going to reach down.
Well, that's what he tried to do.
Yeah, yeah, because it's not going to work.
Well, let's see.
All your years in veterinary medicine, of what are you most proud?
I'm proud of our students.
And I'm particularly proud of our graduate program and the students and how they responded to it.
I think that we did a creditable job with the thing we have in advancing veterinary pathology.
And I think we represented the state quite well.
What else?
Well, I'm proud of the university for what it's done and the state for what it's done to tend back at it.
And I think that sometimes it's a little bit embarrassing how they have protected this institution.
